value.value: The controlled release of acid by a cell or a tissue.
The process by which a symbiont breaches the plasma membrane or cell envelope and enters the host cell. The process ends when the symbiont or its genome is released into the host cell.

definition.value: Viral attachment to the host cell is not part of viral entry in GO because virus attachment does not always lead to viral entry: attachment can also result in the virion being carried by the host cell to another location.

label.value: regulation by virus of viral protein levels in host cell

value.value: Any virus-mediated process that modulates the levels of viral proteins in a cell.
The controlled release of citric acid, 2-hydroxy-1,2,3-propanetricarboxylic acid, by a cell or a tissue.
The controlled release of formic acid, HCOOH, by a cell or a tissue.
The controlled release of lactic acid, 2-hydroxypropanoic acid, by a cell or a tissue.
The controlled release of malic acid, hydroxybutanedioic (hydroxysuccinic) acid, by a cell or a tissue.
The controlled release of oxalic acid, ethanedioic acid, by a cell or a tissue.

label.value: negative regulation by virus of viral protein levels in host cell

value.value: Any process where the infecting virus reduces the levels of viral proteins in a cell.

label.value: positive regulation by virus of viral protein levels in host cell

value.value: Any process where the infecting virus increases the levels of viral proteins in a cell.
Any of the protein subunits that comprise the closed shell or coat (capsid) of certain viruses.
A stable empty viral capsid produced during the assembly of viruses.

label.value: transport of virus in multicellular host

value.value: The transport of a virus between cells in a multicellular organism. The cells can be adjacent or spatially separated (e.g. in different tissues or organs).

label.value: transport of virus in host, cell to cell

value.value: The transport of a virus between adjacent cells in a multicellular organism.

label.value: transport of virus in host, tissue to tissue

value.value: The transport of a virus between tissues in a multicellular organism.
The process in which a capsid acquires another membrane envelope, subsequent to acquiring an initial membrane envelope.
The exit of a viral particle from a host cell that does not involve cell lysis.
The exit of a fully formed virion particles from the host cell by exocytosis via a host vesicle.

A viral process by which enveloped viruses acquire a host-derived membrane enriched in viral proteins to form their external envelope. The process starts when nucleocapsids, assembled or in the process of being built, induce formation of a membrane curvature in the host plasma or organelle membrane and wrap up in the forming bud. The process ends when the bud is eventually pinched off by membrane scission to release the enveloped particle into the lumenal or extracellular space.
A viral budding that starts with formation of a membrane curvature in the host Golgi membrane.
A viral budding that starts with formation of a curvature in the host plasma membrane around which the virion particle assembles.

label.value: viral budding from endoplasmic reticulum membrane

value.value: A viral budding that starts with formation of a membrane curvature in the host ER membrane.
A viral budding that starts with formation of a membrane curvature in the host nuclear membrane.

label.value: viral budding from inner nuclear membrane

value.value: The envelopment of a virus, in which the nucleocapsid evaginates from the host inner nuclear membrane system into the perinuclear space, thus acquiring a membrane envelope.

label.value: viral budding from outer nuclear membrane

value.value: The envelopment of a virus, in which the naked capsid evaginates from the host outer nuclear membrane system, thus acquiring a membrane envelope.

label.value: symbiont-mediated suppression of host translation termination

value.value: A process in which a symbiont inhibits or disrupts translation termination of host mRNAs. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

label.value: suppression by virus of host intracellular interferon activity

value.value: Any viral process that results in the inhibition of interferon activity within the host cell.

label.value: suppression by virus of host cytokine production

value.value: Any viral process that results in the inhibition of host cell cytokine production.

label.value: symbiont-mediated suppression of host antigen processing and presentation of peptide antigen via MHC class I

value.value: A process by which a symbiont inhibits or disrupts the normal processing and presentation of a peptide antigen on its cell surface in association with an MHC class I transmembrane protein complex. One mechanism of suppression is by direct inhibition of host tapasin, a type I transmembrane protein essential for the optimal expression of stable MHC class I molecules on the host cell surface. By inhibiting host tapasin activity, some viruses can prevent presentation of their antigens at the cell surface, and thereby evade the host anti-viral immune response.
The phosphorylation by a protein of one or more of its own amino acid residues (cis-autophosphorylation), or residues on an identical protein (trans-autophosphorylation).

label.value: symbiont-mediated suppression of host mRNA splicing

value.value: A process in which a symbiont inhibits or disrupts the splicing of host mRNA, thus interfering with normal host protein production. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the transcription of the viral genome.

label.value: viral mRNA export from host cell nucleus

value.value: The directed movement of intronless viral mRNA from the host nucleus to the cytoplasm for translation.
The addition of tubulin heterodimers to one or both ends of a microtubule.

label.value: viral replication complex formation and maintenance

value.value: The process of organizing and assembling viral replication proteins in preparation for viral replication.
The process of restoring viral DNA after damage or errors in replication.
Binding to a receptor on the host cell surface.
Binding to a virion, either by binding to components of the capsid or the viral envelope.
The directed movement of a virus, or part of a virus, into, out of, or within a host cell.
The refolding and structural rearrangements of individual capsid subunits to transition from the intermediate procapsid, to the more stable capsid structure.
A multimeric ring of proteins through which the DNA enters and exits the viral capsid.

label.value: exit of virus from host cell nucleus by nuclear egress

value.value: The directed movement of an assembled viral particle out of the host cell nucleus by budding and fusion through the nuclear membranes. In this process, enveloped viral particles are formed by budding through the inner nuclear membrane. These perinuclear enveloped particles then fuse with the outer nuclear membrane to deliver a naked capsid into the host cytoplasm.
A complex of proteins that form a scaffold around which the viral capsid is constructed.
The assembly and maintenance of the viral scaffold around which the viral capsid is constructed.

definition.value: See also the cellular component term 'viral scaffold ; GO:0046806'.

value.value: Globular nuclear domains where the transcription and replication of the viral genome occurs. More than one site can be present simultaneously.
Binding to the extracellular matrix of a host cell.
Binds to and stops, prevents or reduces the activity of histone deacetylase, which catalyzes of the removal of acetyl groups from histones, proteins complexed to DNA in chromatin and chromosomes.
Binding to the surface of a host cell.

label.value: receptor-mediated virion attachment to host cell

value.value: The process by which a virion attaches to a host cell by binding to a receptor on the host cell surface.

label.value: coreceptor-mediated virion attachment to host cell

value.value: The process by which a virion attaches to a host cell by binding to a co-receptor on the host cell surface.
